{% import "macros.njk" as macro with context %}
{% slide %}
    <p><span data-annotate>So you want to be a web developer...</span></p>
    <p>What's that, you don't? Okay, no problem!</p>
    <p>This rough guide is going to have some information that's specific to the work of coding, but the most of this will apply to anyone looking to work on the web.</p>
{% endslide %}
{% slide %}
    <div class="related-post">
        <strong>Related post: <em>Different jobs in a web project</em></strong>
        <p>If you want to learn about all the many jobs & careers related to building stuff on the web, check out our related post:{% br %}<a class="related-post__link" href="/web-life-cycle/">Different jobs in a web project <img src="/images/page-link.svg" alt="Link to another page" class="related-post__icon" height="150" width="150"></a></p>
    </div>
{% endslide %}
{% slide %}
    <p>If you <em>do</em> want to write code for a living, however, let me congratulate you on a good career choice.</p>
    <p>There's good reason to believe that a coding career is {# {% ext "https://whoisnnamdi.com/never-enough-developers/" %}future-proof{% endext %} #}{% ext "https://www.indeed.com/career-advice/finding-a-job/recession-proof-industries" %}recession-proof{% endext %}, {% ext "https://news.ycombinator.com/item?id=29808376" %}future-proof{% endext %}, and a pretty good job to have when {% ext "https://medium.com/coderbyte/how-the-covid-19-pandemic-is-impacting-software-development-hiring-72243f41ac9e" %}everyone suddenly needs to work at home for a few years.{% endext %}</p>
{% endslide %}
{% slide %}
    <p>Over the past decade, the demand for people who can code for the web has skyrocketed. Coding "boot camps" have sprung up, offering to teach you the latest skills in a matter of months, with a focus on what employers are looking for in the moment.</p>
{% endslide %}
{% slide %}
    <p>These boot camps have increased the signal-to-noise ratio for recruiters, making it harder to distinguish candidates with working knowledge from those who have only a superficial grasp on a concept.</p>
    <p>As a result, it has become somewhat harder to get your foot in the door, particularly for those just starting out, and especially in remote-only work.</p>
{% endslide %}
{% slide %}
    <p>Don't let this discourage you, though. The government (where I am, in Canada), has 'web developer' as a top-rated job prospect for the next ten years in the majority of provinces.</p>
    <figure>
        {% ext "https://explore-labour-market.service.canada.ca/viz?page=outlooks&lang=en&noc=2175&geo=0&view=#4/60.45/-89.08" %}{% image "images/prospects.png", "Map showing web developer job prospect ratings by province, with all provinces rated 2 out of three or 3 out of three.", "(min-width: 30em) 1200px, 100vw", "Map via explore-labour-market.service.canada.ca" %}{% endext %}
        <figcaption>Via {% ext "https://www.jobbank.gc.ca/marketreport/outlook-occupation/17892/ca" %}jobbank.gc.ca{% endext %}</figcaption>
    </figure>
{% endslide %}
{% slide %}
    <blockquote><p>"The skills typically required in this occupation are usually standard worldwide... [a]s a result, there are lower barriers for immigrants to become web designers and developers... simplifying their entry and permanency in the country."</p><footer><cite>{% ext "https://www.jobbank.gc.ca/marketreport/outlook-occupation/17892/ca#:~:text=The%20skills%20typically,in%20the%20country." %}Government of Canada: Job Bank{% endext %}</cite></footer></blockquote>
{% endslide %}
{% slide %}
    <p>I love that the web is providing jobs that provide a decent living (even to weirdos like me), and help establish people who want to come live where I am!</p>
    <p class="callout emphasis">Also, the {% ext "https://www.jobbank.gc.ca/outlookreport/location/22437" %}Job Bank trend analysis{% endext %} has pretty fascinating labour market data overall, so have fun with that!</p>
{% endslide %}
{% slide %}
    <p>Okay, so how do you actually <em>get</em> one of these jobs? Let's start by <span data-annotate data-ann-color="var(--alert)">figuring out what skills you need</span>, and how to get them.</p>
{% endslide %}
{% separator "waves" %}
{% section toc[0].href %}
    {% slide %}
        <img src="/images/building-skills.svg" alt="Building skills" height="306" width="406" class="body-icon body-icon--x-large">
        <h2>{% if toc[0].smallTitle %}<div class="small-title">{{toc[0].smallTitle}}:</div>{% endif %}{{ toc[0].title | allGas | safe }}</h2>
    {% endslide %}
    {% slide %}
        <p>As I mentioned a moment ago, there are <a href="/web-life-cycle/">many different jobs involved</a> in building stuff on the web. Similarly, there are many different jobs that could fall under the umbrella of "web development", too! You could be focussed on databases, or user interface design; you could specialize in data security, or performance, or architecting <abbr title="Application Programming Interface">API</abbr>s. Regardless of where you end up, <span data-annotate>you have to start somewhere</span>.</p>
        <p>That "somewhere" is the internet - how it works (loosely), and a few relatively simple languages that make up the core web technologies.</p>
    {% endslide %}
    {% slide %}
        <p>For the record, I'm not going to teach you this stuff today.</p>
{% endslide %}
{% slide %}
        <p>In fact, a lot of this stuff, I will <em>never</em> attempt to teach you, for the simple reason that <span data-annotate data-ann-type="underline" data-ann-color="var(--warning)">the web is absolutely stuffed with free learn-to-code resources</span>. I'm never going to waste your time (or mine!) explaining something if I know that you can learn it elsewhere, as well or better, for free - I'm just going to point you in the right direction!</p>
{% endslide %}
{% slide %}
        <p>Of the free resources that are available, some are great, most are mediocre, and a lot are absolutely lousy. What few of them do is provide <span data-annotate data-ann-type="underline">context and guidance</span>. This, along with <span data-annotate data-ann-type="underline">networking</span> and <span data-annotate data-ann-type="underline">personalized feedback</span>, is essentially the value proposition of all web development classes (whether at a bootcamp or a college or wherever).</p>
{% endslide %}
{% slide %}
        <p>The web is built using technologies that are extensively documented and free to use, which means that <span data-annotate>everything you need to learn is public knowledge.</span> Knowing how it all fits together is the hard part.</p>
        <p>With that in mind, I'd like to share with you a couple of wonderful resources that map out exactly <span data-annotate data-ann-type="underline">where you can start</span>, <span data-annotate data-ann-type="underline">how to progress</span>, and, later on, where you might <span data-annotate data-ann-type="underline">branch off into a specialization</span> (once you're ready).</p>
    {% endslide %}
{% endsection %}
{% section %}
    {% slide %}
        <h3>Roadmap.sh</h3>
        <p>A project begun and curated by {% ext "https://github.com/sponsors/kamranahmedse" %}Kamran Ahmed{% endext %}, {% ext "https://roadmap.sh/" %}Roadmap.sh{% endext %} is based on the input of hundreds of developers, and is one of the most popular projects on Github ({% ext "https://github.com/search?o=desc&q=stars%3A%3E100000&s=stars&type=Repositories" %}#6, as of this writing{% endext %}, with nearly 200,000 stars ‚≠ê).</p>
    {% endslide %}
    {% slide %}
        <p>Roadmap.sh shows learning paths in flow-chart format, with links to recommended resources for each "node".</p>
        <figure>
            {% ext "https://roadmap.sh/frontend" %}
                {% image "images/snippet-of-roadmap.png", "A snippet of a flowchart from Roadmap.sh", "(min-width: 30em) 1200px, 100vw", "Via roadmap.sh" %}
            {% endext %}
            <figcaption>Just a snippet of the front-end roadmap</figcaption>
        </figure>
{% endslide %}
{% slide %}
        <p>Roadmap.sh has paths for many different types of developers, not just web developers. It divides web development paths into "frontend" and "backend".</p>
{% endslide %}
{% slide %}
        <p>While I'd argue that this isn't as important a distinction as it used to be, it very roughly boils down to:</p>
        <dl>
            <dt>Frontend developer</dt>
            <dd>A frontend developer is responsible for things that happen <span data-annotate data-ann-type="underline">in the browser</span> - a website or web app's styles and links and buttons and content.</dd>
            <dt>Backend developer</dt>
            <dd>A backend developer is responsible for things that happen on the other end - the website's files waiting to be requested, data stored in databases that gets retrieved or updated by the website, and stays in memory after you leave.</dd>
        </dl>
{% endslide %}
{% slide %}
        <p>This is a painfully broad description of these two roles, and ignores the fact that these two roles have a ton of overlap, and can include or exclude some of these responsibilities, depending on the organization. If it's a smaller organization, they might just have one "fullstack" developer responsible for everything.</p>
        <p>This is just to say that I think you should take Roadmap.sh's taxonomy with a grain of salt, but don't let that take away from the enormous amount of value it provides.</p>
    {% endslide %}
{% endsection %}
{% section %}
    {% slide %}
        <h3>A simpler roadmap from Flavio Copes</h3>
        <p>Roadmap.sh can seem like a lot - each node is a deep rabbit hole that you could spend endless time exploring, and nobody is there to tell you, "that's enough learning for now, time to move on".</p>
        <p>That's why I'd like to also show you {% ext "https://flaviocopes.com/roadmap-web-developer-2022/" %}a much simpler roadmap{% endext %} that, rather than being the output of countless developers by consensus, is the opinion of some guy. Luckily, it's a very smart, thoughtful, and experienced guy who helps tons of people with their web careers - Italian computer engineer {% ext "https://flaviocopes.com/" %}Flavio Copes{% endext %}.</p>
{% endslide %}
{% slide %}
        <p>Copes' roadmap starts where every web career journey starts, with the big 3: HTML, CSS, and JavaScript. He then shares his opinions about a backend language for the server, a database, and a framework to help handle the data, state and composition of your site or application.</p>
{% endslide %}
{% slide %}
        <p>I don't share all of his opinions, but I respect the heck out of his experience, teaching and writing. My recommendation: <span data-annotate>check 'em both out</span>, figure out what resources are best <em>for you</em> to learn the basics of HTML, CSS & JavaScript, and go from there!</p>
    {% endslide %}
{% endsection %}
{% separator "dots" %}
{% section toc[1].href %}
    {% slide %}
        <img src="/images/school.svg" alt="Learning by yourself" height="306" width="406" class="body-icon body-icon--x-large">
        <h2>{% if toc[1].smallTitle %}<div class="small-title">{{toc[1].smallTitle}}:</div>{% endif %}{{ toc[1].title | allGas | safe }}</h2>
{% endslide %}
{% slide %}
        <p><span data-annotate>All coders teach themselves.</span></p>
{% endslide %}
{% slide %}
        <p>Some of them also get a degree, or go to a bootcamp, or get other certifications.</p>
{% endslide %}
{% slide %}
        {% ext "https://insights.stackoverflow.com/survey/2021#section-experience-learning-how-to-code" %}{% image "images/learn-to-code.png", "Survey responses from Stack Overflow", "(min-width: 30em) 1200px, 100vw", "Via Stack Overflow's 2021 Developer Survey" %}{% endext %}
        <p>A slim majority went to a traditional college or university, about 40% took an online course, and 10% went to a bootcamp.</p>
{% endslide %}
{% slide %}
        <p>The most popular way to learn, though, is by watching Youtube videos and reading blog posts and online documentation.</p>
{% endslide %}
{% slide %}
        <p>The simple fact is <span data-annotate data-ann-color="var(--alert)">no course or college or bootcamp can teach you everything</span> that you will need to know over the course of your career. <span data-annotate data-ann-style="underline">The web keeps changing, and will always keep changing</span> - thanks both to new versions of existing languages, and with new languages, tools, frameworks and techniques altogether.</p>
{% endslide %}
{% slide %}
        <p>Whether or not you <em>start</em> by teaching yourself (which, for many people, is a cheap, viable option), you will need to teach yourself as you go, forever.</p>
        {% ext "https://twitter.com/CatMcGeeCode/status/1418592423865950212" %}{% image "images/cat-mcgee.png", "Tweet by Cat McGee: 'Got a CV today and the guy literally listed one of his skills as ‚Äògoogling‚Äô. We‚Äôre interviewing him'", "(min-width: 30em) 1200px, 100vw", "@CatMcGeeCode" %}{% endext %}
{% endslide %}
{% slide %}
        <p class="callout warning">
            One side effect of this: basically all developers suffer from a permanent case of {% ext "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Impostor_syndrome" %}imposter syndrome{% endext %} for about the first decade of their careers. Everybody feels like they don't know what they're doing, because they're perpetually having to learn something new!
        </p>
{% endslide %}
{% slide %}
        <h3>{{"Where to start teaching yourself" | allGas | safe}}</h3>
        <p>There are a ton of potential starting places, and everyone has a different learning style, so I couldn't possibly tell you in good faith that there is one place to start your learning journey over all the others.</p>
{% endslide %}
{% slide %}
        <p>Or at least that's what I'd say if it weren't for {% ext "https://www.theodinproject.com/" %}The Odin Project{% endext %}.</p>
        <figure>
            {% image "images/odin-project-logo.png", "The Odin Project Logo", "(min-width: 30em) 600px, 100vw", "ATTR" %}
            <figcaption>Odin Project logo by {% ext "https://dribbble.com/adachiu" %}Ada Chiu{% endext %}</figcaption>
        </figure>
{% endslide %}
{% slide %}
        <p>The Odin Project is free, open-sourced (based on the input of hundreds of independent contributors), and has a sterling reputation. It is a great introduction to HTML, CSS and JavaScript (along with version control, which is an essential part of a coding workflow, via {% ext "https://git-scm.com/" %}git{% endext %}).</p>
{% endslide %}
{% slide %}
        <p class="callout alert">I strongly recommend learning <em>something</em> about these "web fundamentals" <strong>before</strong> you start any formal (i.e. paid) learning, be it a college program, a bootcamp, or a paid course. You will get a lot more value if you are not starting with nothing. A lot of free resources available for these fundamentals are really, really good!</p>
    {% endslide %}
{% endsection %}
{% section %}
    {% slide %}
    <h3>Other great places to learn stuff</h3>
    <p>There are <em>lots</em> of great places to start learning for free. If the Odin Project isn't your style, or you want to supplement your learning, or you want to learn something it doesn't cover, there's a ton more stuff out there!</p>
{% endslide %}
{% slide %}
    <h4>Fundamentals - HTML, CSS, JavaScript (and more!)</h4>
{% endslide %}
{% slide %}<div class="callout d-box">
        <div class="d-box__title">{% ext "https://www.freecodecamp.org/" %}freeCodeCamp{% endext %}</div>
        <hr>
        <p>‚Üí freeCodeCamp is a non-profit that, if you complete their certifications, connects students with non-profit organizations to do real (good) work, helping people and building a r√©sum√© at the same time. They offer courses in the fundamentals, plus all kinds of other fun stuff like Quality Assurance, the Python language, Information Security and Machine Learning. Really great stuff!</p>
    </div>
    {% endslide %}
{% slide %}<div class="callout d-box">
        <div class="d-box__title">The {% ext "https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Learn" %}Mozilla Developer's Network{% endext %}</div>
        <hr>
        <p>‚Üí MDN is the absolute best source of documentation on the languages that power the web, and their learning program is great, too! While the tone and formatting might feel vaguely intimidating to some, most people who work on the web will find themselves reading MDN resources regularly (so you might as well get used <span class="no-breaks">to it üòâ).</span></p>
    </div>
{% endslide %}
{% slide %}
    <h4>Python</h4>
    <p>Python is the {% ext "https://insights.stackoverflow.com/survey/2021#section-most-popular-technologies-programming-scripting-and-markup-languages" %}5<sup>th</sup> most popular language{% endext %} among professional developers, behind only HTML, CSS, JavaScript and the database language SQL. It's tremendously popular for being easy to learn, and is used for AI and Machine Learning, Data Analysis, and to run the back end of websites. While JavaScript can famously do all the things (working on the server, interacting with your database, and creating interactivity on your website), many people find Python a better place to start when it comes to serious programming.</p>
    {% endslide %}
{% slide %}<div class="callout d-box">
        <div class="d-box__title">{% ext "https://automatetheboringstuff.com/" %}Automate the Boring Stuff with Python{% endext %}</div>
        <hr>
        <p>‚Üí One of the most fun things you can do with code is to <span data-annotate>make your own life easier</span>. This book, the entirety of which is <span data-annotate data-ann-type="underline">free to read online</span>, teaches you to create automations that can send emails and texts, create and populate spreadsheets, fetch information from websites, and lots more! It assumes you are an absolute beginner, and takes you through some fundamental computer programming concepts, while giving you practical examples of how you might be able to save yourself hours of boring grunt-work at the computer.</p>
    </div>
    {% endslide %}
{% slide %}<div class="callout d-box">
        <div class="d-box__title">{% ext "http://introtopython.org/" %}Intro to Python{% endext %}</div>
        <hr>
        <p>‚Üí Pretty dry, but highly recommended by {% ext "https://old.reddit.com/r/learnpython/wiki/index" %}r/learnpython{% endext %}, particularly for people who have never touched a line of code before in their lives.</p>
    </div>
{% endslide %}
{% slide %}
    <h4>{{"Free College Courses on Computer Programming" | allGas | safe}}</h4>
    <p>An absolutely shocking number of colleges and universities, particularly computer science heavyweights, have been putting their <span data-annotate data-ann-type="underline">course materials and textbooks online <em>for free</em></span> lately, at least as far as their "intro" courses go. I'll link to a few examples here, but definitely check out {% ext "https://collegecompendium.org/" %}College Compendium{% endext %}, which maintains a searchable catalogue of free, publicly available computer science college resources.</p>
    {% endslide %}
{% slide %}<div class="callout d-box">
        <div class="d-box__title">{% ext "https://pll.harvard.edu/course/cs50-introduction-computer-science?delta=0" %}CS50: Introduction to Computer Science{% endext %}</div>
        <hr>
        <p>‚Üí Probably the most famous free university course on the internet. Get an introduction to computer science, and languages including C, PHP, JavaScript, SQL, CSS, and HTML. <em>"Where'd you learn how to code?"</em>  Oh, yah know... <strong>Harvard.</strong></p>
    </div>
    {% endslide %}
{% slide %}<div class="callout d-box">
        <div class="d-box__title">{% ext "https://see.stanford.edu/Course/CS106A" %}CS106A - Programming Methodology{% endext %}</div>
        <hr>
        <p>‚Üí Want to get introduced to computer science by a former Senior Research Scientist at Google, while learning the language that powers Android? Or are left-coast vibes just more your speed? Learn programming methods and concepts that will go with you, whatever your language of choice, by taking this free course from <strong>Stanford University</strong>.</p>
    </div>
    {% endslide %}
{% slide %}<div class="callout d-box">
        <div class="d-box__title">{% ext "https://ocw.mit.edu/courses/res-6-013-ai-101-fall-2021/" %}AI 101{% endext %}</div>
        <hr>
        <p>‚Üí Want to train a machine learning algorithm, but you don't even know how that's a thing? Get a free introduction to Artificial Intelligence from <strong><abbr title="Michigan Institute of Technology">MIT</abbr></strong>!</p>
    </div>
    {% endslide %}
{% slide %}<div class="callout d-box">
        <div class="d-box__title">{% ext "https://cybersecuritybase.mooc.fi/" %}Cyber Security Base 2022{% endext %}</div>
        <p>‚Üí I watched {% ext "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hackers_(film)" %}Hackers{% endext %} at a very impressionable age, so it might just be me, but this introduction to cybersecurity from the <strong>University of Helsinki</strong> seems deeply cool. Their Department of Computer Science has a ton of {% ext "https://www.mooc.fi/en/" %}other free courses{% endext %} to choose from as well!</p>
    </div>
{% endslide %}
{% slide %}
    <h4>Shout out to librarians</h4>
    {% endslide %}
{% slide %}<div class="callout d-box">
        <div class="d-box__title">Your {% ext "https://www.torontopubliclibrary.ca/search.jsp?N=4288098632+4288175358" %}Local Library{% endext %}</div>
        <hr>
        <p>‚Üí I am a <span data-annotate data-ann-color="var(--emphasis)">massive fan of public libraries</span>, and they're not just for books! (That being said, physical books are a {% ext "https://insights.stackoverflow.com/survey/2021#section-experience-learning-how-to-code" %}phenomenally popular learning resource{% endext %} among professional developers - so check 'em out!) I'm very fortunate to live in a city with a phenomenal library system, where they have free classes on, among many other things, Python, Blender (for 3D modelling), Arduino (for "Internet of Things" devices), and plenty more, for both adults and kids! Want to learn how to code? <span data-annotate>Ask your friendly neighbourhood librarian.</span></p>
    </div>
{% endslide %}
{% slide %}
    <h4>Paid Resources I Recommend</h4>
{% endslide %}
{% slide %}
    <p>Because of the wealth of free, open sources for learning fundamentals, I'm hesitant to recommend any paid resources for introductory materials. That being said, there are two creators I'd like to call out, because they create resources that are...</p>
    <ul>
        <li>incredibly fun, creative and approachable,</li>
        <li>meticulous, and</li>
        <li>offer a mix of free and paid content.</li>
    </ul>
{% endslide %}
{% slide %}
    <p>I'm <strong>not</strong> recommending them because they're both Canadian. (But do I enjoy that fact? Yes, yes I do.)</p>
    {% endslide %}
{% slide %}<div class="callout d-box">
        <div class="d-box__title">{% ext "https://jvns.ca/" %}Julia Evans{% endext %}</div>
        <p>‚Üí Julia Evans has an incredible talent for making the most arcane parts of internet infrastructure <span data-annotate>somehow actually fun</span>. She creates {% ext "https://jvns.ca/projects/" %}interactive web projects{% endext %} and {% ext "https://jvns.ca/" %}compelling blog posts{% endext %}, and also inexpensive {% ext "https://wizardzines.com/" %}illustrated 'zines{% endext %} on topics including CSS, git and SQL. She is legitimately my hero.</p>
    </div>
    {% endslide %}
{% slide %}<div class="callout d-box">
        <div class="d-box__title">{% ext "https://wesbos.com/" %}Wes Bos{% endext %}</div>
        <p>‚Üí Wes Bos is the host of the very popular web dev podcast <span class="no-breaks">{% ext "https://syntax.fm/" %}Syntax{% endext %},</span> and offers a mix of {% ext "https://wesbos.com/courses" %}free and paid courses{% endext %} which a lot of folks I know absolutely adore. His focus is on JavaScript and JavaScript frameworks, and his {% ext "https://wesbos.com/javascript" %}notes on beginner JavaScript{% endext %} are a terrific free resource.</p>
    </div>
    {% endslide %}
{% endsection %}
{% separator "chevrons" %}
{% section toc[2].href %}
    {% slide %}
        <img src="/images/camp.svg" alt="Camping" height="306" width="406" class="body-icon body-icon--x-large">
        <h2>{% if toc[2].smallTitle %}<div class="small-title">{{toc[2].smallTitle}}:</div>{% endif %}{{ toc[2].title | allGas | safe }}</h2>
{% endslide %}
{% slide %}
        <p><span data-annotate data-ann-color="var(--alert)">Learning by yourself is hard.</span> It takes a ton of discipline, and if something doesn't work, it can be really frustrating to figure out <em>what went wrong</em>.</p>
        <p>On the other hand, a program at a traditional college or university is a big commitment. You're probably going to have to quit your job, and just be a student for a year (or several). If you have a specific job title in mind, some of the topics that get covered might not feel relevant to your goals.</p>
{% endslide %}
{% slide %}
        <p>If only there was somewhere you could go to learn exactly what the job postings are asking for, in less time than a traditional institution.</p>
{% endslide %}
{% slide %}
        <p>Guess what? That's exactly what coding bootcamps (promise to) do!</p>
        <p>Which brings us to a contentious question: <span data-annotate>do bootcamps deliver?</span></p>
{% endslide %}
{% slide %}
        <p>I feel confident in saying that this question, over which so much digital ink has been spilled, has a boring answer: <span data-annotate data-ann-color="var(--emphasis)">some do, for some people.</span></p>
{% endslide %}
{% slide %}
        <h3>Before you Bootcamp</h3>
        <p>I can strongly recommend, before you even consider bootcamps, <span data-annotate data-ann-type="underline">invest several weeks' worth of free time in teaching yourself the basics</span>. As mentioned earlier, there are a lot of great free resources to get you started. That way you'll know if you can <span data-annotate data-ann-type="underline">learn to love the work</span>. It would suck if you put down thousands of dollars only to quickly discover that you hate everything about the job. And if you <em>do</em> end up pursuing a bootcamp (or any other paid program), you'll get more value out of it than if you are scrambling to figure out the basics.</p> 
{% endslide %}
{% slide %}
        <h3>Return on (a significant) investment</h3>
        <p>We've already established that you'll never learn everything you need to know from a single source, so the question is not "do bootcamps teach you everything?", but rather "do bootcamps make you money?". Full-time bootcamps cost, on average, {% ext "https://globalnews.ca/news/4811078/coding-bootcamp-canada/#:~:text=Full%2Dtime%20programs%20cost%20around%20%2412%2C000%2C%20according%20to%20data%20viewed%20by%20Global%20News%2C%20while%20prices%20for%20part%2Dtime%20classes%20range%20from%20a%20few%20hundred%20to%20a%20few%20thousand%20dollars." %}about $12,000 in Canada{% endext %}, promising that you'll increase your salary by a significant amount, thus justifying the expense.</p>
{% endslide %}
{% slide %}
        <p>It's at this point that it's important we talk about a big caveat:</p>
        <div class="callout alert post-only">
            <h4>Accurate numbers about coding bootcamps are hard to come by</h4>
            <p>Bootcamps, with few exceptions, are unaccredited and operate with little to no oversight. Nearly all don't qualify you for student loans. Some are "partnered" with traditional institutions, while others are entirely independent, without even the reputation of a larger institution to back them up.</p>
            <p>This has lead to a reputation for {% ext "https://nymag.com/intelligencer/2020/02/lambda-schools-job-placement-rate-is-lower-than-claimed.html" %}bogus{% endext %} {% ext "https://twitter.com/fulligin/status/1452658647994015748?s=20&t=f9GbrnhHhQmZWQU9ljVmQw" %}claims{% endext %} and {% ext "https://twitter.com/lzsthw/status/1212284566431576069" %}shady business practices{% endext %}. (Seriously, if you are thinking of attending a bootcamp, actively seek out anti-bootcamp opinions and consider them.)</p>
            <p><span data-annotate>Reliable hard data about outcomes for bootcamp attendees simply does not exist for the industry as a whole.</span></p>
            <p>Additionally, when researching a bootcamp, take anything you read with a grain of salt. Remember that the internet is the main marketing channel for these organizations, and expect them to be very good at optimizing search results. Their value proposition could be (somewhat cynically) described as optimizing r√©sum√©s to get the desired results from the {% ext "https://careers.workopolis.com/advice/beat-automated-resume-screening/#:~:text=More%C2%A0than%2060%25%20of%20companies%20use%20some%20sort%20of%20automated%20screening%20(you%20might%20have%20heard%20of%20this%20referred%20to%20as%20an%20applicant%20tracking%20system)%20to%20streamline%20their%20hiring%20process" %}disturbingly popular{% endext %} automated "resume parsers" (a.k.a. <abbr title="Applicant Tracking System">ATS</abbr>'s). So naturally, these businesses would take SEO seriously (and be good at it, too).</p>
            <p>Also - just between you and me - a lot of the comments I read on reddit or hacker news that endorse the bootcamp experience can read a little... fishy. At very least, personal anecdotes of success are just that: anecdotes.</p>
